🛍️ Store Sales & Profit Analysis using Python
This project analyzes a retail store's sales and profit data to uncover insights across time, categories, sub-categories, and customer segments. The goal is to support data-driven decisions for marketing, pricing, and inventory strategies.

🎯 Objective
To analyze the store’s sales and profit performance by:
Understanding trends across months
Identifying top-performing product categories
Analyzing profitability by customer segments
Deriving actionable business recommendations

🧰 Tools & Libraries
Python
Pandas – Data manipulation
Plotly – Interactive visualizations
CSV – Raw dataset (Sample Superstore)

📁 Dataset Summary
File: Sample - Superstore.csv

Key features:
Order Date, Ship Date, Category, Sub-Category
Sales, Profit, Segment, Quantity, Discount

🔍 Key Analyses Performed
📆 Time-Based Trends
Created features: Order Month, Year, Day of Week
Identified monthly sales and profit trends

📊 Category-Level Insights
Furniture, Technology, and Office Supplies compared by:
Total sales
Total profit
Monthly seasonality

🧠 Sub-Category Analysis
Analyzed top sub-categories driving revenue (e.g., Chairs, Phones, Binders)
Assessed profit contribution by sub-category to identify underperformers

👥 Segment-Level Profitability
Segments: Consumer, Corporate, Home Office
Calculated and compared:
Total sales vs. total profit
Sales-to-profit ratio

📈 Key Findings
Consumers drive the highest profit overall, but Corporate has the most efficient sales-to-profit ratio (7.67).
Furniture generates high sales but comparatively lower profit, hinting at potential margin issues.
February and November show noticeable peaks in sales, useful for campaign planning.
Some sub-categories like Tables and Bookcases generate high sales but poor profits.
